g 17. magistratus...unde in senatum. The rule was deter- mined by the Leae Ouinia qua sanctum est ut censores eae omni ordine optimum quemque iurati in senatum leycrent. The ordines in question were doubtless the different orders of the magis- traeies, commonly thought to be curule offices only. But these would not have been numerous enough to fill up the vacancies that would occur, and the Ovinian law was passed by a tribune, and probably extended the right to the plebeian magistracies. Cf. VVillems Senat. p. 188.
